```python
import torch

from tqdm import tqdm
from datasets import load_dataset
from torch.nn import functional as F

def calculate_wikitext_perplexity( 
        model: torch.nn.Module, 
        tokenizer, 
        device: str,
        sequence_length: int = 1024,
    ):

    # Load the wiki test test.
    dataset = load_dataset('wikitext', 'wikitext-2-raw-v1', 'test')
    text = ''.join(dataset['test']['text'])

    # Encode the text.
    encodings = tokenizer(text, return_tensors='pt')
    max_length = sequence_length
    stride = max_length // 2
    lls = []

    for i in tqdm( range(0, encodings.input_ids.size(1), stride) ):
        begin_loc = max(i + stride - max_length, 0)
        end_loc = min(i + stride, encodings.input_ids.size(1))

        trg_len = end_loc - i
        input_ids = encodings.input_ids[:,begin_loc:end_loc].to(device)
        target_ids = input_ids.clone()
        target_ids[:,:-trg_len] = -100

        with torch.no_grad():
            outputs = model(input_ids.to(device), labels=target_ids.to(device))
            log_likelihood = outputs[0] * trg_len

        lls.append(log_likelihood)

    perplexity = torch.exp(torch.stack(lls).sum() / end_loc)
    return perplexity.item()

def calculate_falcon_perplexity( 
        model: torch.nn.Module, 
        device: str,
        pages,
        sequence_length: int = 1024,
    ):
    dataset = pt.dataset.SubsetFalconLoader(
        batch_size = 3,
        sequence_length = sequence_length,
        pages = pages
    )
    # Load the wiki test test.
    lls = []
    num = 0
    for batch in tqdm( dataset ):
        # Perform a forward pass with the model to compute the loss
        inputs = batch.to( device )
        outputs = model(inputs, labels = inputs)
        loss = outputs.loss.detach().item() 
        lls.append( loss )
        num += 1
    perplexity = torch.exp( torch.tensor(lls).sum() / num )
    return perplexity.item()
```

@slump Hi there! I believe that the default modeling code of `BartForCausalLM` might have some problem. @Deleted User I urge the dev team to update the `pretraining.validation.compute_losses` function (PR submitted too).

`BartForCausalLM.forward` has the following:

```
loss = None
if labels is not None:
```

```
shift_logits = logits[..., :-1, :].contiguous()
shift_labels = labels[..., 1:].contiguous()

loss_fct = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
shift_logits = shift_logits.view(-1, model.config.vocab_size)
shift_labels = shift_labels.view(-1)
```

@Deleted User @Deleted User  I found out why, Here is the paper of https://arxiv.org/pdf/1907.11692.pdf. There are two type of pretrain model: generative model (gpt related ) vs discriminative model (bert, roberta, etc). The difference is that generative model can be used to generate sentence,  discriminative model cannot and only will be used in encoding related problem such as classification, retrieve-based summarization etc.  The reason is that during pretraining, generative model will use previous token to predict next token. discriminative model will make use of whole context, In other words, It will use the latter token as well. As a result, discriminative  will take advantage of this context and the prediction of next token is not based on previous token (Which is lead to data leakage).
The miner here just take advantage of how the discriminative model made prediction. and again its a data leakage issue, thats why the loss is that low
The roberta will never be used in generative task. Because in real generation task, we won't what the latter context is. And I believe generative ability is what we compete here
